TY  - JOUR
AU  - Bloom, Nicholas
AU  - Sadun, Raffaella
AU  - Van Reenen, John
T1  - The Organization of Firms Across Countries*
PY  - 2012
Y1  - 2012/11/01
DO  - 10.1093/qje/qje029
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 127
IS  - 4
SP  - 1663
EP  - 1705
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - We argue that social capital as proxied by trust increases aggregate productivity by affecting the organization of firms. To do this we collect new data on the decentralization of investment, hiring, production, and sales decisions from corporate headquarters to local plant managers in almost 4,000 firms in the United States, Europe, and Asia. We find that firms headquartered in high-trust regions are significantly more likely to decentralize. To help identify causal effects, we look within multinational firms and show that higher levels of bilateral trust between the multinational’s country of origin and subsidiary’s country of location increases decentralization, even after instrumenting trust using religious similarities between the countries. Finally, we show evidence suggesting that trust raises aggregate productivity by facilitating reallocation between firms and allowing more efficient firms to grow, as CEOs can decentralize more decisions.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/qje/qje029
ER  - 



